.env

///
Verdict
  EcoTrack is close. The project already has a good interview story because it is not just CRUD: it has graph modeling, Tarjan articulation points, cycle
  detection, a priority queue, and a real full-stack flow. But to be properly resume-ready, I would tighten the engineering story before the feature list.

  Must Fix

  - Clean the repo hygiene first. Right now the repo is tracking .env, build output under dist, and dependencies under node_modules, and there is
    no .gitignore. That is the fastest way to make the repo look unpolished.
  - Add real test, build, and lint scripts in package.json:7. At the moment you only have dev scripts plus a Tarjan smoke test. I verified npm run
    tarjan:smoke passes, and npx vite build passes, but there is no standard build/test workflow for an interviewer to run.
  - Either implement a real simulation engine or stop calling it a simulation so strongly. The current “simulation” in client/core/FoodChain.js:137 is a
    graph-distance heuristic after species removal, not a time-based ecological model. If you present this as Lotka-Volterra or dynamic systems modeling,
    an interviewer will immediately probe that gap.
  - Fix consistency and validation in the domain model. The schema in server/models/species.js:44 allows very loose strings, while trophic logic is
    inferred from text matching in client/core/speciesUtils.js:78. That makes scores and graph behavior depend on naming conventions instead of explicit
    data.
  - Make sandbox apply atomic. In client/core/SandboxMode.js:18, the app deletes one species and then updates the rest sequentially. If one request fails
    mid-way, your live ecosystem becomes partially applied. A batch backend endpoint or Mongo transaction would make this much stronger.
  - Move seeding out of the client path. [client/core/EcosystemRepository.jsClose, but not fully interview-ready yet. The project already has enough
    substance to discuss well: full-stack CRUD, graph visualization, Tarjan-based analysis, ecosystem scoring, and sandboxed impact analysis. I also
    verified that npm run tarjan:smoke passes and npx vite build succeeds, although the build warns about a large bundle.

  Must Fix

  - Repo hygiene is the biggest red flag. Add a .gitignore, stop tracking .env, and remove tracked node_modules/ and dist/ from git. That matters more
    than any feature.
  - Add real project scripts in package.json:7. Right now there is no build, test, or lint, so a reviewer has no standard way to verify quality.
    ecosystem inconsistent. This should be one backend operation or a DB transaction.
  - Remove automatic seeding from normal app flow in client/core/EcosystemRepository.js:42. Demo data should come from an explicit seed command, not a
    hidden side effect.

  Should Do

  - Fix naming/polish issues like SImulation.html in client/index.html:18, client/ControlPanel.html:19, and README.md:154. Small mistakes weaken first
    impressions.
  - Add a deployed demo, screenshots, or a short walkthrough video. That usually matters more than one extra feature.
  - Add ARCHITECTURE.md and ALGORITHMS.md. This project has enough logic that good docs would make it much stronger in interviews.
  - Tighten form validation and UX in client/pages/controlPanel.js:203. Right now add/update flows are inconsistent, and core rules like invalid prey
    references are not strongly enforced.
  - Reduce the frontend bundle size or at least note the tradeoff. The current Vite build reports a chunk over 500 kB.

  If you want the shortest path to “resume ready,” do these five first: repo hygiene, build/test/lint scripts, 6-10 algorithm tests, explicit schema
  validation, and either a real simulation or a more honest feature name. After that, add a hosted demo and you can defend this project well in
  interviews.

⚠ Heads up, you have less than 25% of your weekly limit left. Run /status for a breakdown.
///
